1. What Are ARIA Attributes?
ARIA = Accessible Rich Internet Applications
ARIA attributes help assistive technologies (like screen readers) understand what an element does.

Example problem:
A visually styled button made with a <div> might look like a button, but a screen reader doesn't know it’s a button.
ARIA fixes this.
Example:              <div role="button">Submit</div>
Now screen readers interpret it as a button.

2. Why ARIA Exists
Web pages today use lots of custom UI components:
                    dropdown menus
                    modals
                    tabs
                    sliders
                    accordions
But these are often built with <div> elements.
Without ARIA:
            screen readers can't understand them
            keyboard navigation breaks
            accessibility fails
ARIA adds semantic meaning.

3. Basic ARIA Structure
ARIA attributes usually start with:  aria-
Examples:
            aria-label
            aria-hidden
            aria-expanded
            aria-live
            aria-controls
            aria-describedby

4. Visual Example: Screen Reader Interpretation
Normal Button      [ Submit ]
Screen reader reads:    "Submit button"

Styled Div (Without ARIA)    [ Submit ]
Screen reader reads:         "Submit"
It doesn't know it's clickable.

Styled Div With ARIA
<div role="button">Submit</div>

Screen reader reads:
"Submit button"
Now it understands the interaction type.

5. Important ARIA Attributes

aria-label
Provides a label for elements.
Example:       <button aria-label="Close menu">X</button>
Visual:        [X]

Screen reader says:    "Close menu button"
This is common in icon buttons.

aria-hidden
Hides elements from screen readers.
Example:     <span aria-hidden="true">★</span>
Visual:      ★ Star icon
Screen reader ignores the star.

aria-expanded
Used for dropdowns and accordions.
Example:      <button aria-expanded="false">Menu</button>
Visual:       Menu ▼
If open:     <button aria-expanded="true">Menu</button>
Screen reader says:    "Menu expanded"

aria-describedby
Provides extra description.
Example:     <input type="password" aria-describedby="passwordHelp">
             <p id="passwordHelp">Password must contain 8 characters</p>
Screen reader reads:     Password input. Password must contain 8 characters.


6. Real Industry Example: Accessible Dropdown
                          HTML
                          <button aria-haspopup="true" aria-expanded="false">
                            Options
                          </button>

                          <ul role="menu">
                            <li role="menuitem">Edit</li>
                            <li role="menuitem">Delete</li>
                          </ul>

Visual:   [ Options ▼ ]
              Edit
             Delete
Screen reader understands:  menu button
                            menu items

7. Accessible Modal Example
Example:  
                      <div role="dialog" aria-labelledby="title">
                      <h2 id="title">Delete Item</h2>
                      <p>Are you sure?</p>

                      <button>Cancel</button>
                      <button>Delete</button>
                      </div>

Screen reader reads:
                      Dialog
                      Delete Item
                      Are you sure?
This helps users know a modal has opened.


8. ARIA Roles (Very Important)
Roles tell assistive tools what an element represents.
Examples:
            role="button"
            role="dialog"
            role="menu"
            role="navigation"
            role="tab"
            role="alert"

Example:
            <div role="alert">
              Payment failed
            </div>
Screen reader immediately announces:      Alert: Payment failed


9. Visual Example: Tabs Component
Tabs UI:          [ Overview ] [ Reviews ] [ Pricing ]
                          Overview Content

Accessible version:

                      <div role="tablist">
                      
                      <button role="tab" aria-selected="true">
                      Overview
                      </button>
                      
                      <button role="tab">
                      Reviews
                      </button>
                      
                      <button role="tab">
                      Pricing
                      </button>
                      
                      </div>

Screen reader understands:
                          tab list
                          active tab
                          navigation structure

10. Golden Rule of ARIA (Important)
Use native HTML whenever possible.

Good:
        <button>
        <input>
        <select>
        <nav>

Avoid:
          <div role="button">

Why?
Because native HTML already has accessibility built in.
ARIA is mainly for custom components.

11. Bad ARIA Example
❌ Bad:
              <div role="button">Click</div>

Better:
              <button>Click</button>

Because <button> already supports:
keyboard navigation
screen readers
focus

12. Common ARIA Attributes Cheat Sheet
Attribute                              	Purpose
aria-label	                        Accessible name
aria-hidden	                    Hide from screen readers
aria-expanded	                      Dropdown state
aria-live	                          Announce updates
aria-controls	                  Controls another element
aria-describedby	                Extra description
aria-checked	                      Checkbox state


13. Example of aria-live
Used in dynamic content like notifications.
Example:
              <div aria-live="polite">
              Message sent
              </div>
Screen reader announces the update automatically.

14. When Companies Use ARIA
ARIA is heavily used in:
                        Google Material UI
                        Microsoft Fluent UI
                        React component libraries
                        Government websites
                        Banking apps
Because accessibility compliance (WCAG) is often required.

15. Interview Question Example
Q: What is ARIA in HTML?
Answer: ARIA (Accessible Rich Internet Applications) is a set of attributes used to improve accessibility by providing additional semantics to HTML elements, enabling assistive technologies like screen readers to better interpret dynamic web content.

